<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www-istp.gsfc.nasa.gov/Education/Figures/Imgintro.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
 Would getting past the magnetosphere be enough? The solar wind sweeps the magnetosphere out away from the sun in a &quot;tail&quot; trailing well beyond the planet. If we therefore launch toward the Sun we have less Magnetosphere to penetrate. Perhaps this would be an opportunity to gather some extra momentum from a sun gravity assist. <br>
It's difficult to be precise about where the Magnetosphere starts and finishes. Some scientists would say it stretches from the Sun to the Earth. Wouldn't a hundred kilometres be enough? The Emp range for those tiny pulse units wouldn't be all that great. Your dish network won't even flicker. A solar flare would have more impact.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://spaceflight.nasa.gov/shuttle/support/processing/srb/images/towlines.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
Would it be worthwhile to orbit the Moon for awhile? Precious little resources worth the effort of sending a fully fueled Shuttle down there from the cargo bay. We might possibly extract some rocket fuel from the Rocks but fetching it by Shuttle would use up a lot of chemical fuel. Unless we use a NERVA powered Shuttle, but then we are wasting reactor energy to get chemical propellant. It would be easier all around to simply mine an Asteroid for volatiles instead. Still, doing burnouts on the Moon in a big Nuclear Dune Buggy would be a lot of fun. Perhaps just a one week stopover before heading out.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://spaceflight.nasa.gov/shuttle/support/processing/srb/images/srb.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
Something reusable like the SRB would cut down on launch costs enormously for an extensive launch program. They'd need parachutes for reentry and they might burn up falling from such an altitude but those aren't unsurmountable problems. For a single launch however, we could dispense with retrievability measures. Thus saving weight. Maybe we need more than a modified SRB. We could scale up the design aswell. Less boosters means less chance of one failing. Ofcourse, it also means greater loss of thrust if one does go awry. I've been trying to find the costs for SRB manufacture. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.ghg.net/redflame/launch.htm">Source.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
1. Fuel is only 0.4 percent of total cost.<br>
<br>
If it takes 100 lbs of kerosene and LOX to put a pound of payload in orbit, with propellants on the order of $0.20/lb, this only accounts for $20/lb. of payload, out of something like $5,000-10,000/lb.<br>
<br>
2. Man-hours of skilled labor account for the remaining 99.6% of Terrestrial launch costs.<br>
<br>
No wonder Russia launches rockets so cheaply. Maybe then we should use volunteers and negate 99.6% of our launch costs in one stroke. Workers, instead of being wage earners, become shareholders, who have signed a contract to work for the program in exchange for a distribution of the profits. A very simple, straightforward and above all fair proposal which would benefit all parties. By putting management and employees in the same boat they will all row together to achieve a common goal. Your Orion is launched for Peanuts and everybody gets rich on the spoils of space resources. <br>
<br>
