<br>
The thrust on an SRB stays constant, while its weight drops.  <br>
<br>
For example, a large SRB weighs a million pounds full and 100,000 pounds empty.  It produces 2,000,000 pounds of thrust.<br>
<br>
With no extra payload, it leaves the pad at a vigorous 2g's of acceleration, because it is thrusting twice as much as it weighs.<br>
<br>
Right before it burns out, it is still thrusting at 2,000,000 pounds, but it NOW weighs only 100,000 pounds.<br>
<br>
20 g's of acceleration.  Okay, sure, the SRB is plenty tough enough to take it.  But if YOU'RE on it, or you are trying to launch a delicate instrument, etc, etc.<br>
<br>
Oh, as a note, in the past SRB's tend to give a REALLY rough ride, lots of vibration as the rubber inside them rattles around as the gases vent.<br>
<br>
<br>
When you're tinkering with staging, you have to keep an eye on the g-loads at the END of each stages burn, not at the beginning.  Indeed, once you get a few miles high, it is usually sensible to make each stage start its burn at a half a g or less.  Smaller engines weigh less.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Now, if ya go with nuclear, you can quit worrying about all this crap.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 121<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/26/02 11:59:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Pro's and Con's of heavy booster assisted Orion.</span><hr size=1> ProjectOrion: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> How do I calculate the figures for a 10,000 ton Orion? Could I simply multiply Mauk2's results for a 2000 ton Orion by five? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
